04837nam a22006015i 9780822382898DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19861986ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223828987 a10.1515/97808223828982doi  a(DE-B1597)553501  a(OCoLC)1226680283  a(OCoLC)1136202548  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPS153.N5bH6 1986 7aLIT0040202bisacsh1 aHogue, W. Lawrence, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDiscourse and the Other :bThe Production of the Afro-American Text /cW. Lawrence Hogue. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1986] 4cÂ©1986  a1 online resource (205 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tChapter 1. Literary production: a silence in Afro-American critical practice -- tChapter 2.The dominant American literary establishment and the production of the Afro-American text -- tChapter 3. Sixties' Social Movements, The Literary Establishment, And The Production Of The Afro-American Text -- tChapter 4. History, The Black Nationalist Discourse, And The Autobiography Of Miss Jane Pittman -- tChapter 5. History, The Feminist Discourse, And The Third Life Of Grange Copeland -- tChapter 6. History, The Blues Idiom Style, And Train Whistle Guitar -- tChapter 7. The Song Of Morrison's Sula: History, Mythical Thought, And The Production Of The Afro-American Historical Past -- tChapter 8. The Post-Sixties, The Ideological Apparatus, And The Afro-American Text -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe central thesis of Lawrence Hogue's book is that criticism of Afro-American literature has left out of account the way in which ideological pressures dictate the canon. This fresh approach to the study of the social, ideological, and political dynamics of the Afro-American literary text in the twentieth century, based on the Foucauldian concept of literature as social institution, examines the universalization that power effects, how literary texts are appropriated to meet ideological concerns and needs, and the continued oppression of dissenting voices.Hogue presents an illuminating discussion of the publication and review history of "major" and neglected texts. He illustrates the acceptance of texts as exotica, as sociological documents, or as carriers of sufficient literary conventions to receive approbation. Although the sixties movement allowed the text to move to the periphery of the dominant ideology, providing some new myths about the Afro-American historical past, this marginal position was subsequently sabotaged, co-opted, or appropriated (Afros became a fad; presidents gave the soul handshake; the hip-talking black was dressing one style and talking another.)This study includes extended discussion of four works; Ernest J. Gaines's The Autobiography of Miss Jane Pittman, Alice Walker's The Third Life of Grange Copeland, Albert Murray's Train Whistle Guitar, and Toni Morrison's Sula. Hogue assesses the informing worldviews of each and the extent and nature of their acceptance by the dominant American cultural apparatus.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aAfrican Americans in literature. 0aAfrican AmericansxIntellectual life. 0aAmerican literaturexAfrican American authorsxHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aCanon (Literature). 0aCriticismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aDiscourse analysis, Literary. 0aLiterature and societyzUnited States. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822382898zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttp